nd African Americans through the early 1960s. Vitalis pairs the contributions of white and black scholars to reconstitute forgotten historical dialogues and show the critical role played by race in the formation of international relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aImperialismxHistoriography. 0aInternational relationsxStudy and teaching (Higher)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacism in higher educationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aDiscrimination & Race Relations. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History.  aimperialism, racism in higher eduction, race relations, race relations in 20th century, racism and imperialism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170188740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701887423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701887/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles